üî• Detailed Explanation of Each Category
üî∂ 1. Network-Based Attacks
Attacks that target the network or communication channels.

‚úî DoS / DDoS (Denial of Service)
Overloads the target server to make it unavailable.

‚úî MITM (Man-in-the-Middle)
Intercepts communication between two systems.

‚úî Sniffing
Captures unencrypted network packets (passwords, data).

‚úî Spoofing
Pretending to be someone/something else
(ex: IP spoofing, Email spoofing).

‚úî Session Hijacking
Taking control of an active session (cookies stolen).

‚úî DNS Poisoning
Redirects users to fake malicious websites.

üî∂ 2. Malware Attacks
Malicious software installed on a system.

‚úî Virus
Attaches to files & spreads when the file runs.

‚úî Worm
Self-spreading without user action.

‚úî Trojan
A ‚Äúfake‚Äù useful program that contains hidden malware.

‚úî Ransomware
Encrypts files and demands money to unlock.

‚úî Spyware
Steals sensitive information silently.

‚úî Adware
Shows unwanted ads and tracks user behavior.

üî∂ 3. Human-Based (Social Engineering) Attacks
Tricks humans instead of exploiting systems.

‚úî Phishing
Fake emails or messages to steal login credentials.

‚úî Spear Phishing
Targeted phishing for specific individuals.

‚úî Pretexting
Attacker creates a fake story to get information.

‚úî Baiting
Offering something enticing (USB, downloads) to trap users.

‚úî Tailgating
Entering secure areas by following authorized people.

üî∂ 4. Advanced Application & System Attacks
‚úî Zero-Day Attack
Exploits a software vulnerability not yet known to the vendor.

‚úî SQL Injection
Injecting malicious SQL commands into input fields.

‚úî Cross-Site Scripting (XSS)
Injects malicious scripts into trusted websites.

‚úî CSRF (Cross-site Request Forgery)
Tricks a logged-in user into performing malicious actions.

‚úî Password Attacks
Brute force

Dictionary attack

Credential stuffing

‚úî Insider Threat
Employees intentionally or accidentally leaking data.

‚úî Supply Chain Attack
Targets vendors to compromise the final organization.

