ChatGPT said:
Here are the most common cyber attacks that generally occur in real-world systems. These are the attacks you are most likely to encounter or hear about regularly.

‚úÖ Common Cyber Attacks (Real-World)
1. Phishing
Fake emails/messages trick people into revealing passwords or clicking malicious links.

Example:
"Your bank account is locked ‚Äî click here to verify."

2. Malware
Any malicious software installed without user consent.

Types include:

Virus

Worm

Trojan

Ransomware

Spyware

Adware

Example:
You download a ‚Äúfree tool‚Äù that secretly steals data.

3. Ransomware
Encrypts your files and demands payment to unlock.

Example:
WannaCry, LockBit attacks on hospitals & companies.

4. Password Attacks
Attackers try to guess or steal passwords.

Methods:

Brute force (trying all combinations)

Dictionary attack

Credential stuffing (using leaked passwords)

5. DoS / DDoS (Denial of Service)
Attackers overload a server with traffic to make it unavailable.

Example:
Website becomes slow or unreachable due to massive requests.

6. MitM (Man-in-the-Middle)
Attacker intercepts communication between two parties.

Example:
Connecting to an unsecured WiFi network.

7. SQL Injection
Attacker injects malicious code into a website‚Äôs database query.

Example:
Login form bypass: ' OR '1'='1

8. XSS (Cross-Site Scripting)
Attacker injects malicious scripts into trusted websites.

Example:
Stealing cookies/session tokens.

9. Social Engineering
Attacks that exploit human behavior instead of technical vulnerabilities.

Includes:

Fake calls

Impersonation

Fake support agents

Tailgating into office buildings

10. Insider Threat
An internal employee/contractor misuses access intentionally or accidentally.

Example:
Employee leaking data.

11. Spoofing
Pretending to be someone else (email, IP, caller ID).

Example:
Fake emails appearing to come from CEO.

12. Zero-Day Attack
Using a vulnerability unknown to the vendor (no patch available).

13. Supply Chain Attack
Attackers compromise a vendor to reach their customers.

Example:
SolarWinds attack (affecting thousands).